<subSubSection id="C33311E1FFEA7F0399F7E66AD6A7F921" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8B96426AFFEA7F0399F7E66AD208FAD6" blockId="47.[151,1436,1230,1675]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis id="B95D9E78FFEA7F0399F7E66AD53DFA85" bold="true" box="[198,559,1301,1327]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Distribution and ecology:—</emphasis>
The Guayana Highlands in southeastern 
<collectingCountry id="F33E02FAFFEA7F039D1EE66AD3B5FA85" box="[1071,1191,1301,1327]" name="Venezuela" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
(to be expected in adjacent 
<collectingCountry id="F33E02FAFFEA7F039837E643D675FAFC" box="[262,359,1340,1366]" name="Guyana" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Guyana</collectingCountry>
) and the Andes in northwestern 
<collectingCountry id="F33E02FAFFEA7F039BCFE643D46DFAFC" box="[766,895,1340,1366]" name="Venezuela" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F33E02FAFFEA7F039ABCE643D31BFAFC" box="[909,1033,1340,1366]" name="Colombia" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F33E02FAFFEA7F039D26E643D36DFAFC" box="[1047,1151,1340,1366]" name="Ecuador" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry id="F33E02FAFFEA7F039DF3E643D3ECFAFC" box="[1218,1278,1340,1366]" name="Peru" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Peru</collectingCountry>
. Is is locally common along humid forest edges, along roads, on landslides, and along streams at 
<quantity id="4CD1EF8FFFEA7F039D40E61DD204FAD6" box="[1137,1302,1378,1404]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.35" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="1.7" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" unit="m" value="2350.0" valueMax="3000.0" valueMin="1700.0">1700–3000 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B96426AFFEA7F0399F7E6F6D6A7F921" blockId="47.[151,1436,1230,1675]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis id="B95D9E78FFEA7F0399F7E6F6D621FA09" bold="true" box="[198,307,1417,1443]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Notes:—</emphasis>
Morphologically, this species is at the center of a complex of seven closely related species which include: 
<taxonomicName id="4C2939E9FFEA7F0399CEE6CFD6D3FA63" authorityName="Ching" authorityYear="1940" baseAuthorityName="Sodiro" box="[255,449,1456,1481]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="blepharolepis">
<emphasis id="B95D9E78FFEA7F0399CEE6CFD6D3FA63" box="[255,449,1456,1481]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">S. blepharolepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C2939E9FFEA7F0398E1E6CFD574FA63" authorityName="Copeland" authorityYear="1947" baseAuthorityName="Christ &amp; Rosenst." box="[464,614,1456,1481]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="buchtienii">
<emphasis id="B95D9E78FFEA7F0398E1E6CFD574FA63" box="[464,614,1456,1481]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">S. buchtienii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C2939E9FFEA7F039B47E6CFD5C5FA63" authorityName="J. Gonzales" authorityYear="2011" box="[630,727,1456,1481]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="jacha">
<emphasis id="B95D9E78FFEA7F039B47E6CFD5C5FA63" box="[630,727,1456,1481]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">S. jacha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C2939E9FFEA7F039BD6E6CFD473FA63" authorityName="J. Gonzales" authorityYear="2011" baseAuthorityName="J. Gonzales" baseAuthorityYear="2011" box="[743,865,1456,1481]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lanosus">
<emphasis id="B95D9E78FFEA7F039BD6E6CFD473FA63" box="[743,865,1456,1481]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">S. lanosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C2939E9FFEA7F039A41E6CFD307FA63" authorityName="Smith" authorityYear="1990" baseAuthorityName="Cav. ex Sw." box="[880,1045,1456,1481]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tomentosus">
<emphasis id="B95D9E78FFEA7F039A41E6CFD307FA63" box="[880,1045,1456,1481]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">S. tomentosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="4C2939E9FFEA7F039D69E6CFD3D9FA63" authorityName="Copeland" authorityYear="1947" baseAuthorityName="Kunze" box="[1112,1227,1456,1481]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="velatus">
<emphasis id="B95D9E78FFEA7F039D69E6CFD3D9FA63" box="[1112,1227,1456,1481]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">S. velatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Traditionally all seven taxa have been considered to belong to a single, variable species (
<bibRefCitation id="EFB83F9BFFEA7F039AC1E6A8D3E2FA5B" author="Tryon, R. M. &amp; Stolze, R. G." box="[1008,1264,1495,1521]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" pagination="1 - 122" refId="ref34267" refString="Tryon, R. M. &amp; Stolze, R. G. (1989) Pteridophyta of Peru. Part II. 13. Pteridaceae - 15. Dennstaedtiaceae. Fieldiana Botany, n. s. 22: 1 - 122." type="book chapter" year="1989">Tryon &amp; Stolze 1989</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB83F9BFFEA7F039DCDE6A8D641F9BD" author="Ostergaard A. &amp; Ollgaard, E." pageId="47" pageNumber="48" pagination="107 - 169" refId="ref33047" refString="Ostergaard A., Ollgaard, E. &amp; B. (2001) Gleicheniaceae. In Harling, G. &amp; Andersson, L. (eds.), Flora of Ecuador 66: 107 - 169." type="journal article" year="2001">Østergaard &amp; Øllgaard 2001</bibRefCitation>
). In their study of the genus in 
<collectingCountry id="F33E02FAFFEA7F039BDBE682D447F9BD" box="[746,853,1533,1559]" name="Ecuador" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB83F9BFFEA7F039A55E682D3F7F9BD" author="Ostergaard A. &amp; Ollgaard, E." box="[868,1253,1533,1559]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" pagination="107 - 169" refId="ref33047" refString="Ostergaard A., Ollgaard, E. &amp; B. (2001) Gleicheniaceae. In Harling, G. &amp; Andersson, L. (eds.), Flora of Ecuador 66: 107 - 169." type="journal article" year="2001">Østergaard &amp; Øllgaard (2001)</bibRefCitation>
recognized 
<taxonomicName id="4C2939E9FFEA7F039CB4E681D625F997" authorityName="Ching" authorityYear="1940" baseAuthorityName="Sodiro" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="blepharolepis">
<emphasis id="B95D9E78FFEA7F039CB4E681D625F997" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">S. blepharolepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a distinct species. A closer examination of the morphological variability of the complex over its entire geographical distribution has convinced us that there are seven distinct entities, which are treated here at the species level.
</paragraph>
